[[Image:Hermann Paradisus Batavus.jpg|thumb|''Paradisus batavus'' by Paul Hermann, Leyden, 2nd Edn. 1705]]
'''Paul Hermann''' (30 June 1646, [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]] – 29 January 1695, [[Leiden]]) was a German-born physician and botanist who for 15 years as director of the [[Hortus Botanicus Leiden]].
Born in Halle, [[Saxony-Anhalt]], Germany, Paul Hermann was the son of Johann Hermann, a well-known organist, and Maria Magdalena Röber, a clergyman's daughter. Hermann studied theology and medicine in Wittenberg and botany in Leipzig. After graduating from Europe's finest medical school, [[Padua]] in 1670, he was then engaged by the [[Dutch East India Company]] and went to Ceylon (now [[Sri Lanka]]) as a Ship's Medical Officer. He was in their employ from 1672 to 1677. During his stay there, he made a scientific collection of this island's plants and other organisms. He was then offered the job at Leiden and took up the Chair of Botany at the [[Leiden University|University of Leiden]] in 1679 and took up his residence in 1680 at Leiden where he spent the rest of his professional life. He immediately set to making it the finest botanical garden in Europe.
[[File:Hermann Lilium africanum polyanthos.jpg|thumb|''[[Cybistetes|Lilium Africanum Polyanthos]]'' in ''Paradisus batavus'', 1698]] Hermann's ''Paradisus batavus'', a description of the plants of the Leyden university botanical garden, was published three years after his death in 1698 and edited by [[William Sherard]]. There was a second edition published in 1705. Sherard edited his notes and solicited patronage for the publication of this important book. They were students together of [[Joseph Pitton de Tournefort |Tournefort]] in Paris in 1688. This is where Hermann perfected his botanical draughtsmanship. Later Sherard collected more of his notes and produced a catalog published as ''Musaeum Zeylanicum'' (1717, 2nd edn.: 1727). Hermann's original Ceylon collection was used by [[Carl Linnaeus]] when he wrote his ''Flora Zeylanica'' (1747) and [[Species Plantarum|''Species plantarum'']] (1753), using the abbreviation "Hermann herb." in those publications. After Hermann's collections had passed through many hands, they were eventually purchased by Sir [[Joseph Banks]]. Now they are kept at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London. Hermann was a very good [[botanical illustrator]] and had an excellent botanical grasp as declared by Linnaeus himself.
==Works == * ''Cynosura materiae medicae : ante sedecim annos in lucem emissa, brevibusque annotatis exornata a Joh. Sigismundo Henningero, nunc diffusius explanata, et compositorum Medicamentorum Recensione aucta...''. Argentorati : Beck, 1726 [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-169318 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library Düsseldorf]]. * ''Horti Academici Lugduno-Batavi Catalogus.'' 1687 ([https://books.google.com/books?id=8jg-AAAAcAAJ Google Books], [http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/resolve/display/bsb10301782.html BSB]). * ''Florae Lugduno-Batavae flores.'' 1690 ([http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/resolve/display/bsb10301783.html BSB]). * {{cite book|last1=Hermann|first1=Paul|title=Paradisus Batavus, Continens Plus centum Plantas affabre aere incisas & Descriptionibus illustratas; Cui Accessit Catalogus Plantarum, quas pro Tomis nondum editis, delineandas curaverat|url=http://daten.digitale-sammlungen.de/~db/bsb00001273/images/index.html?seite=8|date=1705|origyear=1698|publisher=Elzevier|location=Leiden|edition=2nd}} * ''Cynosura Materiae Medicae…''. Spoor, Straßburg 1710 ([http://www.mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn/resolver.pl?urn=urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb10226700-5 online]; edited by Johann Sigismund Henninger), ([http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-169318 1726 edition] at [[University and State Library Düsseldorf]]).
