'''''Red Bastard''''' is a live [[bouffon]] clown theatre show written and performed by [[Eric Davis (clown)|Eric Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Ben|last=Kharakh|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=26 March 2007|title=Eric Davis, Clown and Buffoon|url=http://gothamist.com/2007/03/26/eric_davis_clow.php|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811070024/http://gothamist.com/2007/03/26/eric_davis_clow.php|archivedate=11 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Funny Kind of Love|first=Ginia|last=Bellafante|date=21 August 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/21/fashion/sundaystyles/21CLOWNS.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Washington Post]]|title=Clowning with the audience|first=Lavanya|last=Ramanathan|date=1 June 2011|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/05/AR2011010505738.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[LA Weekly]]|date=2 August 2012|title=Red Bastard|first=Steven|last=Leigh Morris|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2012-08-02/calendar/red-bastard/full/}}</ref>
==Overview== What begins with a surreal monologue by a twisted clown named Red Bastard<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Scotsman]]|first=Kate|last=Copstick|title=Comedy review: Red Bastard|date=5 August 2013|url=http://www.edinburgh-festivals.com/blog/2013/08/05/comedy-review-red-bastard/}}</ref> quickly devolves into full blown audience participation.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Independent]]|title=Edinburgh 2013: Red Bastard|first=Julian|last=Hall|date=19 August 2013|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/reviews/edinburgh-2013-red-bastard--the-socalled-marmite-of-comedy-actually-tastes-quite-mild-8774074.html}}</ref>
